VERDICT: confirmed-but-no-uca
REASON: Proof-code drift confirmed by inspection of `src/priority.rs:13` (`MAX_PRIORITY: u32 = 32`), `src/thread_lifecycle.rs:569-587` (`priority_set_decide`), and `ffi/src/lib.rs:3957-3962,4003-4042,4264-4275` (all four FFI entry points encode priority as `u32` and compare `< 32`). `ffi/include/gale_thread_lifecycle.h:42,175,182` documents the post-drift predicate "valid (< MAX_PRIORITY)" to C consumers while `zephyr/kernel/include/ksched.h` `_is_valid_prio(int prio)` admits `prio ∈ [-NCOOP, NPREEMPT)` (signed). Kani/PoC oracles are trivially falsified by the unfixed code (no solver run needed): `(uint32_t)(-1) = 0xFFFFFFFF ≥ 32` ⇒ cooperative prio `-1` rejected even though `_is_valid_prio(-1)` is true; `(uint32_t)20 = 20 < 32` ⇒ prio `20` admitted though invalid under `CONFIG_NUM_PREEMPT_PRIORITIES=16`. Interestingness: the drift is not masked by a caller precondition — the FFI header is the authoritative contract and claims the opposite — and the project itself acknowledges signed cooperative priorities in `artifacts/requirements.yaml:3278-3295` (SWREQ-SC-SC14). The finding is real. However, gale's `zephyr/gale_thread_lifecycle.c:593,866` still uses Zephyr's own `Z_ASSERT_VALID_PRIO` / `_is_valid_prio` and has no call site for any of the four gale priority validators in the current C shim, so the direct hazard (OOB into `_priq_*`) is latent until the shim is switched over — but the proof-code drift and propagated spec in the published C header stand on their own. No UCA file exists: `safety/stpa/ucas.yaml` is absent, and `artifacts/stpa.yaml` stops at Step 1c (losses/hazards/system-constraints only, no UCAs). Closest hazard would be H-1 (`artifacts/stpa.yaml:57-71`, "Kernel provides incorrect thread scheduling decision"); a new UCA `TL-UCA-1` ("priority validator admits priorities outside Zephyr's `_is_valid_prio` range, or rejects priorities inside it — STPA UCA-type 2 + UCA-type 3 under H-1") is required before an emission can group this entry.
